=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>bad for your shareholders =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0they=E2=80=99re probably all diversified=C2=A0index funds and can han=
dle the loss =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s very bad for you, because you =
have undiversifiable career risk tied up in your company. The shareholders =
should want you to take big risks, but you might be too nervous. So, the th=
eory goes, the shareholders should give you lots of stock options so you ge=
t asymmetric upside, overcome your natural worries about your career, and t=
ake the optimal amount of risk for the shareholders.</p> <p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Hedge fund managers are arguably=C2=A0less naturally risk-averse=
 than corporate executives, and also get paid for upside (in the form of pe=
rformance fees), so you might think they probably take at least the optimal=
 amount of risk for clients. Still it is perhaps a nice additional incentiv=
e that the career risk of blowing up isn=E2=80=99t really that bad. You jus=
t start a new fund, and when you meet with potential investors you give the=
m a sheepish grin and they make fun of you for a few minutes and then give =
you their=C2=A0money anyway.=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, =
some risk aversion is good, particularly if you are running a multimanager =
fund:</p> <blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Clients note that Veriti=
